n American studies to show how culture is produced in the spaces between empires. With case studies of popular stars like Linda Lin Dai and Edison Chen, and spectacular genres like the Shaolin Temple cycle of martial arts films and the romantic melodramas of 1970s Taiwan, this book explores what it meant to be both cosmopolitan and Chinese in the second half of the twentieth century.Key FeaturesStudies Hong Kong and Taiwan cinemas together, and separately from the cinema of mainland ChinaBrings together perspectives from Chinese studies and Asian American studies to show how culture is produced between empires, in ethnic and racialized ways internationallyProvides a serious take on “trashy” work that has been neglected by scholarship, including: romantic melodramas; martial arts films with seemingly recycled plots and tropes; action films; and music videos  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aMotion picturesxHistoryy20th centuryzChinazHong Kong. 0aMotion picturesxHistoryy20th centuryzTaiwan. 4aFilm, Media & Cultural Studies. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311078043740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978147442847740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474428477423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474428477/original  a978-3-11-078043-7  Edinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK